initial commit of source from project

Replace disklru cache with an equivalent jar

Move centerCrop function into utils
Make classes return runnables to photo managerAllows for uniform scheduling/cancelling interfacenand for all posting to background threads to bendone in one place.n
Add reference counting methods for bitmaps

Cache bitmaps in lru and mutables in memoryRemoves requirement not to use memory cache onndevices that use bitmap recycling because refncounting prevents us from recyling a bitmap thatnis being used for something else (either bynanother view or by a cache). Also removesnrequirement to pass in bitmap to be recycled tonphoto manager, though adds the requirement thatnviews call acquire and release as they use andnrelease bitmapsn

Only hash keys for disk cachedisk cache requires a subset of characters,notherwise it doesn't matter. hashing is expensivencompared to concatenating strings, so usenconcatentation when possible and only hash innbackground.n
Refactor out method to get size of photo on disk

Move getting recycled bitmaps into stream resizerLets us actually determine the size of the bitmapnwe want to load and use that to see if a recyclednone is available. Otherwise we would have to passnin values which would be difficult to keep tracknof. Side affect is we need to get two inputndifferent input streams from the disk cache, onento check the size and one to actually load thenimage.n
Add a max # of bitmaps per size to storeAlso remove some loggingn
Minor code cleanup
Allow PSR to not use recycled bitmapsIncreases the standalone utility of the classn
Allow caching of same photo in different typesAdds an enum to be appended onto keys so that keysnidentify not just the size but also the type ofntype.n
Replace ResizeCallback with LoadedCallbackremoves a redundant callback since both had nessentially the same two methods.
Don't remove all queued items if token == null
Increase # of each bitmap type to keep around
Add presenter system for wrapping imageviews
Track bitmaps using hashcode, not the objectPrevents us from accidently leaking bitmaps ifnwe fail to call acquire and release in the correctnorder.

Loading logic->ImageLoaders, and use weak refsPrevents us from leaking views if a path fetch ornimage load doesn't complete or takes a long time.nAlso better encapsulates loading code so that thenpresenter is entirely independent of the photo nloading code.
Replace thumbnail inheritance with compositionRemoves need to write load checking logic in twonplaces. Use a presenter coordinating interface tonkeep minimal track of the presenter's states.n
Only fetch missing entries in disk cache once
Don't cancel disk cache putsNo point in doing the same work repeatedly, mightnas well eagerly incur the cost of putting to thendisk cache and avoid having to resize again later.n

Increaes the size of the bitmap cache

Rename stream resizer to match what it now does
Use builder pattern for image presenters

Fix a memory leakIf a view hadn't been measured by the time the npath was loaded, the dimens runnable would repostnitself until it was. For views that are invisible,nthis would occur forever, or until the view becamenvisible. If the view never became visible, thenrunnable would be reposted infinitely and retainnits references infinitely -> leaking photo manager

BaseImageLoader manages refs and loader lifecycleAllows simpler callbacks in the presenter ornhigher levels and moves responsibility for not nleaking referneces into the image loader. ALsoncombines ImageLoader and AssetPathConverter ninterface to simplify the external interface andnmake it possible to use a presenter with a modelnthat already has a path or otherwise doesn't neednto fetch one.
Add a way to queue bitmaps that are never aquired
Fix losing track of bitmaps when they are replacedIf the bitmap in the cache were replaced, rathernthan being evicted, the listener would not be nnotified and we would leak a reference.
Use recycled bitmaps when performing a center crop
Pass in correct value if image comes from cache

Release bitmaps when we request a new oneMaximizes potential for recycling, each loader nownonly needs to hold on to at most one bitmap at a ntime. Before it would hold on to the old bitmapnand request a new one, using twice the memory
SimpleAssetPathConverter is not abstract...
Add load to get an image assumed to be given sizeAllows us to skip the somewhat expensive fetch ofnthe image size from the data on disk to retrievena recycled bitmap.

Add a clear method to image loaderAlso don't cancel load tasks. We incur the gcnpenalty early on, so though cancelling might savensome cpu work, it causes more gcing and worsenperformance early on because we toss the allocatednbitmap rather than storing and reusing it.
Add an AsIs photo manager loader

Delay image fetch until view size is stableFixes a case where we load an image for a view npart way through a property animation so whennthe animation finishes the loaded image only fitsnin part of the view.

Don't make subclasses of loaders use internal cbSimplifies subclasses and makes it easier to nmake callbacks leak proof without sacrificingnsafety. If the subclasses have a strong referencenonly to the internal callback, they will not nretain a strong reference to the presenter or thenimage view since the internal callback only has anweak reference to a callback generated by the nimage presenter.

Abort can throw same illegal state as commitSo don't try to abort if disk cache is closed andncatch all errors in error handeling code so wendon't cause a crash trying to abort a failed ncommit

Replace library disk cache with our ownThis is unfortunate, but has to be done becausenthe disklrucache jar is just enough to put us overnthe edge so we run into linear alloc errors onnolder phones. Hopefully this can be reverted in nthe future.

Be more paranoid about threading in disk cacheThis is not really a solution, but in casenopen and close overlap because of actions on nbackground threads started by two differentnimage managers, this will at least let statenbe consistent. Needs more work to avoid thisnproblem.

Handle cache dirs being null + build version checkApparently either get cache dir method can returnnnull in some circumstances. If one does, try thenother, if both do, return null. The image managernwill just not use a disk cache if the cachendir is null. Environment.nisExternalStorageRemovable is api 9+ and we nsupport 8, so add a check before using it.

This change means wenmore aggressively cleanup those resources whennwe think each Drawable is no longer being used.nThe side affect is that we may reset back tonthe beginning of the Drawable in somencircumstances.nnCleanup in in memory resources makes it lessnlikely that frames would be retrieved fromnin memory, so this also works toward #207.n

Use Interface instead of abstract ListPreloader In your examples the ListAdapter and the final ListPreloader are strongly connected. Using an Interface will remove this strong connection.Using an interface that an Adapter can implement has the followingnadvantages:n1. the dimensions donu00c2u00b4t must be passed to the ListPreloader while the Adapter has the first access to the dimensions of the ImageViewn2. you donu00c2u00b4t have to pass the items to the ListPreloader, while thenAdapter already has the newest set of items (e.g.: CursorAdapter)n3. in most cases the ListAdapter already has an RequestBuilder, sonyou donu00c2u00b4t have to pass them twicen4. you get rid of an extra class (ListPrelaoder) you have to implementn

Avoid overflowing read buffer decoding Bitmaps.Fixes #283.nnWe use BitmapFactory.Options#inJustDecodeBounds tondecode the width and height of images beforendecoding the full image so that we can downsamplenlarge images to avoid memory pressure. To do so,nwe use mark/reset on a buffered InputStream. Tonhandle images with large headers, we set a largen(currently 5mb) mark limit. However, there'snalways the chance that that limit is insufficientneven with a well formatted image and a bugnfree decoder. Since downsampling is typically annoptimization, if such a failure occurs we stillnwant to decode the full image, even if we can'tnobtain the dimensions. By enforcing we don't readnbeyond our limit, we ensure that the header readnfails recoverably, so that the full image cannstill be decoded.n

Avoid race where Request snapshot contains null.Our implementation of toArray() called size()nmultiple times, starting with the size used fornthe array. size() in WeakHashMap removes entriesnfrom the map if the corresponding WeakReference nhas been cleared. As a result, if a referencenwas added to WeakHashMap's reference queue betweennour outer call to size() and the methods in ntoArray(), the actual number of entries might havenbeen smaller than our array size, which wouldnlead to one or more null entries at the end of thenSnapshot array.nnFixes #322.

Encode resources after delivering them to callers.Encoding after delivery decreases load times,nsometimes dramatically, when a limited number ofnrequests are active at once. Once all of Glide'snsource threads are busy, this change provides onlyna limited benefit because new requests still havento wait for encodes from previous requests tonfinish. However, when only a few large images arenrequested, particularly with slow encode formatsnlink PNG, images will appear substantially faster.n

Disable cross fade in TransitionDrawable by defaultThe cross fade method in TransitionDrawable controls whether or not thenDrawable transitioned from is faded out.nnIf cross fading is enabled, the old Drawable's alpha is animated fromn100 to 0 while the new Drawable's alpha is animated from 0 to 100. Usingnthis behavior can cause performance problems on older phones andnproduces a whiteout affect in the middle of the transition where bothnDrawables are at 50% opacity but the background color behind thenTransitionDrawable can be seen clearly.nnWith cross fading disabled, the old Drawable's alpha is not animated andnthe new Drawable is simply faded in on top of the old Drawable.nnThis does change the default behavior in Glide. If users prefer the oldnbehavior, they can use DrawableCrossFadeFactory.Builder to re-enablenTransitionDrawable's cross fade.n-------------nCreated by MOE: https://github.com/google/moenMOE_MIGRATED_REVID=122579678n

Use correct any... matchers for primitive numeric parametersMore Information: []nMockito relies on Java type checking to ensure that the matchers are used in antype safe manner. While that works for the most part it does not work wellnfor primitive numeric parameters as Java will do widening conversions if thentypes are not exact, which means that anyInt() can be used for long parameters.nThat has no effect in the current version of Mockito as it does not do typenchecking for the any... matchers. However, future versions do type check andnexpect exact match on type for primitive matchers.nnThis CL fixes the incorrect usages of the any... matchers. The change was madenusing an Error Prone BugChecker and once all the incorrect usages have beennfixed it will be enabled to prevent any other incorrect usages being added innfuture.nnCleanup change automatically generated by error-prone refactoring third_party/java_src/mockito/v1_9_5:mockito_any_incorrect_primitive_type on targets <stripped>nnTested:nTAP --sample for global presubmit queuen[]nn-------------nCreated by MOE: https://github.com/google/moenMOE_MIGRATED_REVID=153880222n

Add an animation executor to decode GIF frames on.Our normal source executor is often used to load data from networks. Glideu00e2u0080u0099s default networking library runs all networking operations on Glideu00e2u0080u0099s source executor. OkHttp runs the initial connection on its ownnthread pool, but we still read and write the body of each request to our ache on Glideu00e2u0080u0099s source executor. Even libraries like Volley that buffernthe entire request into memory will still require a few hundred milliseconds of Glideu00e2u0080u0099s source executoru00e2u0080u0099s time to write the request to ncache.nnScrolling through a list of images will enqueue a large number of requests. If each request is relatively time consuming, itu00e2u0080u0099s likely thatnall of Glideu00e2u0080u0099s source executor threads will end up blocked for nsignificant periods of time, even if the longer requests are lower priority. Using a different executor for GIF frames and other animationsnlets us avoid junk during playback. nnUnfortunately there is a CPU and memory hit to using an additional executor. Iu00e2u0080u0099ve tried to limit that here by using only one or two threadsnand a cached thread pool so that few threads are created and are onlyncreated when an animation is actually run.nnFixes #899

Obtain the correct size Bitmap in TransformationUtils.roundedCorners.Previously we were obtaining the requested image size. The requestednimage size is ignored in roundedCorners because the transformation ndoesnu00e2u0080u0099t scale. As a result we were weirdly stretching the image withnsome combinations of image and requested dimensions.nnFixes #2472.

Add a DrawableTransformation that runs wrapped BitmapTransformations.The transformation uses the same logic used by the ResourceBitmapDecodernto try to convert non-Bitmap Drawables to BitmapDrawables. Avoid recycle Drawables/Bitmaps passed in or loaded from Resources.Both Androidu00e2u0080u0099s Resources class and AppCompat class will cache contentnthey decode. Start a new load with the RequestManager for the destroyed Fragmentn4. Obtain a RequestBuilder from the Fragment RequestManagern3. Pass the RequestBuilder to a background threadn4. Wait for the Fragment to be destroyedn5. Reset DiskLruCachWrapper outside of IOException catch block in clear().DiskLruCache can close the disk cache but throw anyway in delete(), nwhich previously left the disk cache in an unrecoverable state until thenapplication was restarted. By always nulling out the disk cache variablenwe allow for future attempts at opening the disk cache even if closingnit throws. nnThis particular case was caused by a bug in DiskLruCache where it wouldnthrow on an empty directory if the cache were deleted outside the appnwhile the app was still running, but broadly speaking it seems like a nbad idea to allow our disk cache to get into a state where the app mustnbe killed for it to function again, even if we might partially ignorena clear disk cache command (which wouldnu00e2u0080u0099t be retried or recovered in nthe previous implementation anyway).nnFixes #2465.

Avoid obtaining size of recycled Bitmap in logs in BitmapPreFillRunner.If the BitmapPool is too full or the Bitmap is larger than the nBitmapPool size, putting a Bitmap into the pool may recycle it. As a nresult itu00e2u0080u0099s unsafe for us to use the Bitmap after the call to put() in nthe BitmapPool, including in logging. Iu00e2u0080u0099ve resolved the issue by nmemoizing the Bitmap size prior to the put() call.nnFixes #2574.

Catch NPEs and RuntimeExceptions thrown in getActiveNetworkInfo.The framework seems to throw these on various devices and versions ofnAndroid, though mostly on Samsung between APIs 22 and 24. nnThe deleted test was passing because of an exception in isConnected, notnin registerReceiver so it was incorrect. Only avoid restarting old requests when memory cache is disabled, not just setYou can set skipMemoryCache to true or false, or you can not set it atnall. Previously we were avoiding using the previous request ifnskipMemoryCache is set, which means that not setting skipMemoryCachenbehaves differently than setting skipMemoryCache to false. That's notnnecessarily a bug, but it's not expected either. Now we only avoid usingnthe previous request if skipMemoryCache is explicitly set to true.nn-------------nCreated by MOE: https://github.com/google/moenMOE_MIGRATED_REVID=178704109n

Default active resource retention false.Although Glide avoids recycling or mutating Bitmaps recovered fromnactive resources via weak references, we can't prevent callers fromndoing so. If callers do mutate or recycle the Bitmaps, Glide may thrownexceptions, show graphical errors, or experience other undefinednbehavior. Since we can't guarantee that Glide's behavior is safe, itndoesn't make sense to default this option on.nnThat said, recycling or mutating Bitmaps returned by Glide isn'tnstrictly safe either and is generally both bad and inefficient. Ifnapplications use the safe and efficient RequestManager.clear methodninstead, setting this option to true will work as expected. As a result,nwe'll retain the option, but force users to opt in if they want thenbenefit.nn-------------nCreated by MOE: https://github.com/google/moenMOE_MIGRATED_REVID=178704468n

Fix using a recycled DecodeJob object when ResourceEncoders throw.Itu00e2u0080u0099s possible that a ResourceEncoder will throw unexpectedly. If they donso, the exception is caught by the DecodeJobu00e2u0080u0099s top level try/catch block. Unfortunately, in a finally block lower down the stack, we werencalling onEncodeComplete and returning the DecodeJob to the pool. As a result, the logic in the catch block higher up was running after the DecodeJob was already in the pool, causing an exception. Now we avoid calling onEncodeComplete and returning the DecodeJob to the pool if an exception is thrown, which allows the logic in the top level catch block to function as we expect.

Handle null outConfigs from BitmapFactory on API 26.We may be able to be smarter about how we perform this fallback. Notnall images are affected and those that are may be limited to somensubtypes of images. This fix may have negative side affects if it causesnus to use the wrong config for the inBitmap. Although the image shouldnstill decode if we use the wrong config because we retry on failuresnwith a null inBitmap, it can prevent us from re-using Bitmaps and wastenmemory and CPU cycles.

Avoid passing null configs to Bitmap.createBitmap in LruBitmapPool.We already handle null configs for our various strategies because some ntypes of Bitmaps (GIFs mostly) on some API levels will have special nnative configs that have a null Java equivalent. As a result, nLruBitmapPool does not throw as long as there is a matching Bitmap in nthe pool even if the config weu00e2u0080u0099re asked for is null. nnThis change fixes the inconsistent behavior where we would throw ifnthe pool happened to not have a matching Bitmap when the given confignis null. Now we universally handle null configs in get() and getDirty().

Avoid throwing when decoding Files with DiskCacheStrategy.AUTOMATIC.AUTOMATIC allows decoding items from the resource cache in case the itemnbeing loaded is local. If the item is remote and the user is requestingna File however, the resource cache generator will throw an exceptionnbecause itu00e2u0080u0099s unable to find any path that will obtain a File from anynModel. Iu00e2u0080u0099ve fixed this here by special casing Files and ignoring missingnpaths for them in ResourceCacheGenerator so that loads for File typesnwonu00e2u0080u0099t fail with automatic if they would have otherwise succeed withnDiskCacheStrategy.DATA. Iu00e2u0080u0099ve also updated a few of the error messagesnto try to make it clearer why a load has failed if it fails for a nsimilar reason.nnFixes #2824.

Include the debug aar in release artifacts for Android projects.We removed the release variant a while ago to speed up the build, whichnhas the side affect of removing the release aar from artifacts. Sincenwe expect the debug and release variants to be identical (hence whynwe disabled the release variant), it should be safe to just use the ndebug aar instead. We will have to specify it explicitly since androidu00e2u0080u0099snrules unsurprisingly only add the release variant by default.

Create a CachedHashCodeArrayMap subclass to speed up EngineKey hashing.EngineKey is hashed frequently and caches its own hashCode, however for every request a new EngineKey is created and it rehashes the options and transformations. It's common to cache RequestBuilders for generating multiple requests that have the same options so a handy optimisation is to use an ArrayMap subclass that caches the hashCode to prevent recomputing it every time. This is one of the more expensive atoms in starting a glide request.nn-------------nCreated by MOE: https://github.com/google/moenMOE_MIGRATED_REVID=185029279n

Removes Math.round() call when the argument is an integer or a long.Math.round() called with an integer or long type can result in loss of information because it coerces the argument to a float before rounding back to an int.nnIf this CL introduces an explicit saturated cast from long to int, you may want to remove the cast if it wasn't desired. Create a CustomViewTarget to replace ViewTarget.The two main differences are:n- It forces you to override the method where resources must be cleared. Not doing so results in recycled bitmaps being used and crashing apps. Not doing so was a common pattern among developers optimizing for lines of code instead of correctness.n- No more setTag(object) use. Glide now targets 14+ which can safely use the id tag variant and avoid another class of runtime bugs caused by developers optimizing for lines of code instead of correctness by calling setTag() and overwriting Glide's data.nnFinally, we deprecate ViewTarget, SimpleTarget and BaseTarget. Apps should primarily be using Target, CustomViewTarget, ImageViewTarget and FutureTarget which either force the developer to implement all necessary methods, properly implement them themselves, or will not attempt to reclaim bitmaps. The deprecated classes continue to be used internally by some of the correct classes but can be merged down once the deprecated APIs are able to be removed.nn-------------nCreated by MOE: https://github.com/google/moenMOE_MIGRATED_REVID=201729878n

Include Transcode class in cache key for cached resource classes.We've avoided returning resource classes that can't possible bentranscoded to our expected transcode class to avoid uselessly decodingnand then throwing out an unusable resource. Unfortunately when thatnoptimization was implemented we didn't change the cache key used to keepntrack of the set of available resource classes, so the set of resourcesnfor two different transcode class requests could have the same cache keynbut different contents. As a result we introduced a race where a smallernthan accurate (or even empty) set of resource classes could be returnednif the first call to getRegisteredResourceClasses used the same Modelnand Resource class, but a different and less available trascode class.nnThis change includes the transcode class in the cache key so that wenstop incorrectly sharing cache keys across different resource classnsets.nn-------------nCreated by MOE: https://github.com/google/moenMOE_MIGRATED_REVID=210131660n

Retain the hasAlphaBit when rotating images in TransformationUtils.This fixes a bug where camera images written with non-zero exifnorientations are cached in Glide's disk cache as slower PNGs instead ofnJPEGs. Camera images without exif orientaiton or with 0 values for thenexif orientation are unaffected.nnImages with exif orientations are always rotated by Downsampler usingnthis method when they're decoded. The modified method writes the rotatednimage into a Bitmap acquired from the BitmapPool. Bitmaps in the poolndefault to having hasAlpha true because it's safer to retainntransparency than not. The modified method previously did not update thennewly obtained bitmap's hasAlpha flag with the value from the unrotatednoriginal. As a result, every image with exif orientation ended up in anbitmap with the hasAlpha flag set to true. In turn, BitmapEncoder wouldnwrite all of these images to disk as PNGs because it assumes images withnhasAlpha set to true might have transparency. Writing and reading PNGsnis much slower than writing/reading JPEGs in general, so this causes anperformance issue for Camera images, which, as a rule, do not haventransparency (and have hasAlpha set to false).nnTo avoid the performance hit, this change sets the hasAlpha flag onnrotated Bitmaps based on the value from the original unmodified Bitmap.nn-------------nCreated by MOE: https://github.com/google/moenMOE_MIGRATED_REVID=218380242n

Catch/ignore SecurityException opening MediaStore thumbnails.A Uri permission grant for a MediaStore Uri will only grant access to the main Uri, not the thumbnail Uri. Applications that have only Uri permissions and not the storage runtime permissions will receive a SecurityException when they try to open the corresponding thumbnail. nnPrior to this change, the thumbnail exception would cause the entirenrequest to fail. After this change only the thumbnail portion of the request will fail so the image may still be loaded via the original MediaStore Uri. nnFixes #3504.

Require ResourceListener in the constructor of EngineResourceResourceListener is supposed to be effectively final in EngineResource.nIt was only passed into a separate method to reduce the number of passnthroughs. Since we're now loading resources on multiple threads, it's nonlonger trivially safe to call an additional method to set the listener.nnSpecifically there's a race where the EngineJob exposes the Resource tonany new requests for the same image before the Engine has a chance tonset the ResourceListener on the EngineResource. The locking to fix thisnis complicated and would require holding multiple locks simultaneously.nInstead this cl moves the ResourceListener into the EngineResourcenconstructor and performs the necessary pass throughs to make thatnhappen. Ideally this is safer and more performant than adjusting thenlocking.nn-------------nCreated by MOE: https://github.com/google/moenMOE_MIGRATED_REVID=234844998n

Update to Truth 0.45, and address deprecations.Renames may include:n- containsAllOf => containsAtLeastn- containsAllIn => containsAtLeastElementsInn- isSameAs => isSameInstanceAsn- isOrdered => isInOrdern- isStrictlyOrdered => isInStrictOrdernnThe other major change is to change custom subjects to extend raw Subject instead of supplying type parameters. The type parameters are being removed from Subject. This CL will temporarily produce rawtypes warnings, which will go away when I remove the type parameters (as soon as this batch of CLs is submitted).nnSome CLs in this batch also migrate calls away from actualAsString(). Its literal replacement is `< + actual + >` (unless an object overrides actualCustomStringRepresentation()), but usually I've made a larger change, such as switching from an old-style Not true that... failure message to one generated with the Fact API. In that case, the new code usually contains a direct reference to this.actual (a field that I occasionally had to create). Another larger change I sometimes made is to switch from a manual check-and-fail approach to instead use check(...). And sometimes I just remove a withMessage() call that's no longer necessary now that the code uses check(...), or I introduce a check(...) call. Create annotation glide module classes lazily but outside a lock.This means we might instantiate GlideModule classes multiple times ifnmultiple threads race and call Glide.with(). Only one instance willnactually be used even if this happens.nnInstantiating modules outside of a lock allows to both:n1. Provide an opportunity for dependency injection into GlideModulenconstructors without introducing deadlock.n2. Lazily create modules.nnWe could instantiate the modules exactly once if we initialize themneagerly, but that would slow down application startup. We canninstantiate modules exactly once, but can introduce deadlock ifndependency injection is used (Glide.get() acquires the Glide lock, thennthe DI lock. DI.get() acquires the DI lock, then the Glide lock).nnThe primary cost of instantiating (and injecting) glide modules isnprobably in the reflection and class loading. Most of that is alreadynmemoized, so it's not super expensive to do it more than once. Mostnapplications won't race anyway, so most of the time the cost isneffectively non-existent (we hope).nnA future change will allow passing in a Context to the constructornof modules to allow injection in the constructors only.nnPiperOrigin-RevId: 253114941n

Allow AppGlideModules to optionally accept a Context in their constructor.The Context can then be used to safely inject parameters and/or classesnoutside of Glide's initialization lock. The initialization will happennexactly once per AppGlideModule instance, but the lack of a lock meansnthat more than one AppGlideModule instance may be created.nnWe can't both not use a lock and guarantee that initialization willnoccur exactly once. Rare race conditions causing double initializationnare probably worth the cost, especially because most DI frameworks willnmemoize and minimize the cost of the second injection if it does occur.nnPiperOrigin-RevId: 253302453n

Re-implement Request#pause() to allow partial clearing of requests.RequestManager#pauseRequests expects to pause requests that are runningnwithout affecting requests that have completed. From a user perspective,npauseRequests should allow grey squares in a photo grid to remain grey,nwithout affecting any images that have managed to successfully load.nnWithout an interface change it's not possible to apply this behavior tonthumbnail requests where the thumbnail(s) have completed but the fullnrequest has not because clear() applies to all parts of the request,nregardless of whether or not they have completed.nnThe pause() method added in this change allows us to clear() an innprogress full request while leaving any completed thumbnails in place.nAs a result the user may see lower resolution thumbnails untilnRequestManager#resumeRequests is called, but they won't see the lowernresolution thumbnails disappear as soon as RequestManager#pauseRequestsnis called.nnPiperOrigin-RevId: 260725883n

Avoid holding locks when releasing resources.We need to lock while updating the various states of the objects thatncare about resources. We don't need a lock when all we're doing isnreleasing the resource itself. Previously we fixed a deadlock by addingnlocks so that locks were always acquired in order. It appears thoughnthat we can go the other direction for this particular case and avoidnholding any locks, which should also solve the deadlock.nnIf it turns out this doesn't work we can revert this and add anothernlayer of locking when releasing from the memory cache. Ideally thoughnthis should provide better performance with too much more complication.nnFixes #3795nnPiperOrigin-RevId: 260748170n

Distinguish resource set from request complete in Glide's RequestCoordinatorsA request might have it's thumbnail complete, but not it's full. It'snnot complete, but it has a resource set. If it has a resource set, and anparent's request fails, we shouldn't replace the thumbnail with thenerror placeholder.nnComplicating matters is that we have another way in which we want tonknow if a resource is set. SingleRequest wants to know if its the firstnrequest in the set so it can tell its RequestListener.
